## The problem

Keyboard handling in React Native has always been painful — and it is painful in the same way, on every project, every time.

```
"The input is hiding behind the keyboard on Android."
"There's a white flash every time the keyboard opens on iOS."
"I have 8 fields — do I really need 8 refs just to get Next to work?"
```

`KeyboardAvoidingView` behaves differently per platform, per navigation setup, per device height. `KeyboardAwareScrollView` is better, but still leaves you managing refs, `returnKeyType`, and `onSubmitEditing` by hand for every single field.

**FieldFlow solves all of it in one wrapper.**

---

## How it works

<div align="center">
<img src="media/architecture.png" width="600" alt="FieldFlow architecture diagram" />
<br/>
<sub>An internal <code>Animated.Value</code> spacer tracks native keyboard frames and grows/shrinks your layout — no <code>KeyboardAvoidingView</code>, no white-holes, no jumps.</sub>
</div>

<br/>

1. Wrap your fields with `<FieldForm>`
2. Replace `TextInput` with `<FieldInput>`
3. FieldFlow registers every field in mount order
4. `returnKeyType` is set automatically — `"next"` for middle fields, `"done"` for the last
5. Tapping Next scrolls the next field into view and focuses it
6. Tapping Done dismisses the keyboard and calls your `onSubmit`

That's it. No refs, no `blurOnSubmit`, no `onSubmitEditing` wiring.

---

## Installation

```sh
npm install react-native-fieldflow
# or
yarn add react-native-fieldflow
# or
bun add react-native-fieldflow
```

> No native modules · No `pod install` · Works with Expo · React Native ≥ 0.68

---

## Quick start

### Before FieldFlow

```tsx
// 8 fields = 8 refs + 8 onSubmitEditing handlers + platform behavior guessing
const emailRef    = useRef<TextInput>(null);
const passwordRef = useRef<TextInput>(null);

<KeyboardAvoidingView
  behavior={Platform.OS === 'ios' ? 'padding' : 'height'}
  keyboardVerticalOffset={Platform.OS === 'ios' ? 64 : 0}
>
  <ScrollView keyboardShouldPersistTaps="handled">
    <TextInput
      ref={emailRef}
      returnKeyType="next"
      blurOnSubmit={false}
      onSubmitEditing={() => passwordRef.current?.focus()}
    />
    <TextInput
      ref={passwordRef}
      returnKeyType="done"
      onSubmitEditing={handleSubmit}
    />
  </ScrollView>
</KeyboardAvoidingView>
```

### After FieldFlow

```tsx
import { FieldForm, FieldInput } from 'react-native-fieldflow';

<FieldForm onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
  <FieldInput placeholder="Email"    keyboardType="email-address" />
  <FieldInput placeholder="Password" secureTextEntry />
</FieldForm>
```

Same result. A fraction of the code. Works identically on iOS and Android.

---

## Real-world example — sign up screen

```tsx
import { FieldForm, FieldInput } from 'react-native-fieldflow';

export default function SignUpScreen() {
  const handleSubmit = async (values) => {
    await api.post('/register', values);
  };

  return (
    <SafeAreaView style={{ flex: 1 }}>
      <FieldForm onSubmit={handleSubmit} extraScrollPadding={80}>

        <FieldInput
          placeholder="Full name"
          autoCapitalize="words"
          textContentType="name"
        />
        <FieldInput
          placeholder="Email address"
          keyboardType="email-address"
          textContentType="emailAddress"
          autoCapitalize="none"
        />
        <FieldInput
          placeholder="Phone number"
          keyboardType="phone-pad"
          textContentType="telephoneNumber"
        />
        <FieldInput
          placeholder="Password"
          secureTextEntry
          textContentType="newPassword"
        />
        {/* Last field — automatically gets returnKeyType="done" */}
        <FieldInput
          placeholder="Confirm password"
          secureTextEntry
          textContentType="newPassword"
        />

        <Button title="Create account" onPress={handleSubmit} />
      </FieldForm>
    </SafeAreaView>
  );
}
```

Five fields. Zero refs. Pressing Next on field 4 auto-focuses field 5. Pressing Done on field 5 calls `handleSubmit`. Keyboard avoidance is smooth on both platforms.

---

## API reference

### `<FieldForm>`

The core wrapper. Manages the keyboard spacer, scroll behaviour, and the focus chain for all `<FieldInput>` children — at any depth.

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `onSubmit` | `() => void` | — | Called when the last field is submitted |
| `extraScrollPadding` | `number` | `100` | Extra space between the focused field and the keyboard top |
| `scrollable` | `boolean` | `true` | Wrap children in a ScrollView |
| `avoidKeyboard` | `boolean` | `true` | Enable the keyboard avoidance spacer |
| `style` | `ViewStyle` | — | Style applied to the outer container |
| `scrollViewProps` | `ScrollViewProps` | — | Props forwarded to the internal ScrollView |

### `<FieldInput>`

A drop-in for `TextInput`. Accepts every standard `TextInput` prop, plus:

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `shouldIgnoreChain` | `boolean` | `false` | Exclude this field from the focus chain |
| `onFormSubmit` | `() => void` | — | Called only if this is the last field and the user taps Done |
| `nextRef` | `RefObject<TextInput>` | — | Manually point to the next field (overrides auto-chain) |

### Hooks

```tsx
import { useKeyboardHeight, useKeyboardVisible } from 'react-native-fieldflow';

// Current keyboard height in dp — 0 when hidden
const height = useKeyboardHeight();

// Boolean — true when keyboard is on screen
const visible = useKeyboardVisible();
```

**`useKeyboardHeight`** — returns the current keyboard height as a number. Updates on show/hide. Uses `keyboardWillShow` on iOS for a smooth response, `keyboardDidShow` on Android.

**`useKeyboardVisible`** — simple boolean derived from `useKeyboardHeight`. Useful for conditionally rendering a footer, a floating button, or anything that should respond to the keyboard being open.

```tsx
// Example — floating "Save" button that lifts above the keyboard
function FloatingFooter() {
  const height = useKeyboardHeight();

  return (
    <View style={{ position: 'absolute', bottom: height + 16, left: 16, right: 16 }}>
      <Button title="Save changes" onPress={save} />
    </View>
  );
}
```

